A call to Curve.Evaluate will throw an ArgumentOutOfRangeException if no keys have been added to the curve. This scenario however is handled in XNA.

e.g.

var curve = new Curve();
curve.Evaluate(1f);

Suggest adding code similar to the following to fix the issue

MonoGame/MonoGame.Framework/Curve.cs

public float Evaluate(float position)
{
    if (_keys.Count == 0)
    {
        return 0f;
    }               

```
if (_keys.Count == 1)
{
    return _keys[0].Value;
}

//REST OF CODE...
```

Possible unit tests...

```
[Test]
public void EvaluateNoKeys()
{
    var curve = new Curve();

    var result = curve.Evaluate(1.25f);

    Assert.AreEqual(0f, result);
}

[Test]
public void EvaluateOneKey()
{
    var curve = new Curve();
    curve.Keys.Add(new CurveKey(1, -1));

    var result = curve.Evaluate(1.25f);

    Assert.AreEqual(-1f, result);
}
```

See issue...https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/issues/3924

A call to Curve.Evaluate will throw an ArgumentOutOfRangeException if no keys have been added to the curve. This scenario however is handled in XNA.

e.g.

```
var curve = new Curve();
curve.Evaluate(1f);
```

Suggest adding code similar to the following to fix the issue

**MonoGame/MonoGame.Framework/Curve.cs**

```
public float Evaluate(float position)
{
    if (_keys.Count == 0)
    {
        return 0f;
    }               

    if (_keys.Count == 1)
    {
        return _keys[0].Value;
    }

    //REST OF CODE...
```

Possible unit tests...

```
    [Test]
    public void EvaluateNoKeys()
    {
        var curve = new Curve();

        var result = curve.Evaluate(1.25f);

        Assert.AreEqual(0f, result);
    }

    [Test]
    public void EvaluateOneKey()
    {
        var curve = new Curve();
        curve.Keys.Add(new CurveKey(1, -1));

        var result = curve.Evaluate(1.25f);

        Assert.AreEqual(-1f, result);
    }
```

I could create a PR but that may take a little while

Failing test added to 09_Collections.xml. Test fails with `ContentLoadException : Content reader could not be found for CustomEnum type.`

The issue was that when compiling the xml, the custom class gets a `ContentTypeWriter`, but it's `ReflectiveSerializer` is never created because there are no items in the list, which means the `ContentTypeWriter`s for the custom class members are not created. At load time, the reader is created but the element readers can not be found (even though they were not needed!)

[EDIT]
I've found a better way to resolve this. Now, all element and generic arg type writers get added to the `ContentTypeWriter` at the time that their parent writer is added. This is done by the new `internal virtual void OnAddedToContentWriter(ContentWriter)` method. The new virtual method was necessary because using `Initialize` was no good as the `ContentWriter` reference is needed and using `Write` is no good because it won't always be called (empty lists etc).

Also managed to remove this comment :)

```
             // TODO: This is kinda messy.. seems like there could
             // be a better way for generics and arrays to register
             // their inner types with the typeWriterMap
```
